WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.480
Hi everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:14.480
I'm Rachel.

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:17.879
If we haven't met yet, I lead Customer Marketing at Posit.

00:00:17.879 --> 00:00:21.080
I'm so excited to have you joining us today.

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:26.639
The Hangout is our open space to hear what's going on in the world of data across different

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:32.160
industries, chat about data science leadership, and connect with others facing similar things

00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:33.160
as you.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:39.599
We get together here every single Thursday, unless it's a holiday, at the same time, same

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:40.959
place.

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:46.080
If you are watching this as a recording in the future and you want to join us live, there

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:50.000
will be details to add it to your calendar below.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.959
Just a note to make sure it adds it for 12 to 1 Eastern Time.

00:00:53.959 --> 00:00:59.080
I know sometimes people have some issues with the calendar depending on what time zone

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:00.080
you're in.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:05.480
Is this anybody's first Data Science Hangout today?

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:10.680
Say hi in the chat because we'd love to welcome you in and say hello too.

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:14.660
We're all dedicated to keeping this a friendly and welcoming space for everybody and love

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:22.160
to hear from you no matter your years of experience, the languages that you work in, titles, or

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:23.160
industries.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:28.919
It is totally okay for you to just listen in here too and maybe be a part of the party

00:01:28.919 --> 00:01:31.400
that happens in the Zoom chat.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:37.680
There's also three ways you can jump in and ask questions or provide your own perspective.

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:41.120
Hopefully there'll be lots of people providing their own perspective today because you'll

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:43.919
see we're doing things a little bit different today.

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:50.120
First, you can raise your hand on Zoom and I will call on you.

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:55.599
You can put questions into the Zoom chat and just put a little asterisk or star as

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:00.199
I call it next to it if you want me to read it out loud, otherwise I'll call on you to

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:02.120
introduce yourself.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:07.279
And then third, we have a Slido link, which I just remember I forgot to create for today,

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:15.240
so I'll make that as we go, but you can ask questions anonymously there too.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:19.440
Two notes to share just before we jump in.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:25.199
Posit conference is happening in August in Seattle, and I just want to make sure nobody

00:02:25.199 --> 00:02:30.039
misses the announcement that registration is live, so if you are interested in joining

00:02:30.039 --> 00:02:36.199
us, Curtis will share the link in the chat where you can learn more about the conference.

00:02:36.199 --> 00:02:40.960
And then also I am on a mission this year to help connect people who are using Posit

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:43.000
across their own companies.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:48.360
We have a LinkedIn group for the Hangouts, which you can sometimes find people from your

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.679
own organization, but I'd also love to help connect you, so if you want me to help introduce

00:02:53.679 --> 00:02:59.000
you to people across your organization who we maybe are already working with, feel free

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.759
to use this just simple Google form I made.

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:08.720
But with that, thanks so much for joining us today, and as I mentioned, we are doing

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:14.919
things a little bit different today, and so what that means is today there's actually

00:03:14.919 --> 00:03:17.160
no single featured leader.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.360
You all are the featured leaders today.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:28.160
So last year we had a Hangout where this leader had to reschedule last minute, and we had

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:33.279
this open week, and it turns out the Hangout crew really liked that format, so we said

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:38.679
once in a while we're going to have these open sessions where everybody can jump in

00:03:38.679 --> 00:03:42.279
as the featured leader and share their experience.

00:03:42.279 --> 00:03:45.639
So if this is your first Hangout today, you're going to see this is a little bit different

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:47.639
than how they normally go.

00:03:47.639 --> 00:03:53.880
Normally there's one featured leader here sharing their experience, but I'm really excited

00:03:53.880 --> 00:04:00.119
to hear from all of you today, and so I was thinking I'll kick it off with a topic, but

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:04.679
I want to see from all of you in the chat, too, what are some things you want to talk

00:04:04.679 --> 00:04:11.600
about today or maybe dive deeper into things we've talked about in past weeks.

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:14.360
We sometimes refer to this as chaos mode as well.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:18.440
I see Mark put that into the chat.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:25.239
I get a little bit of nervous energy for these, which is exciting, too, but the first thing

00:04:25.239 --> 00:04:32.679
I wanted to chat about is I know the value of relationships has come up so much in different

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:38.239
data science Hangouts, and we talked about this with so many different leaders, and so

00:04:38.239 --> 00:04:41.079
I was curious to hear from you all.

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:48.279
How do you network within your own organizations, and how do you build relationships with people

00:04:48.279 --> 00:04:49.839
across the company?

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:55.119
I think especially as so many of us work remotely, this can be something that's really hard to

00:04:55.119 --> 00:05:02.160
do, so I'm just curious to learn from all of you if somebody wants to jump in and raise

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:06.559
their hand and share what they have, too.

00:05:06.559 --> 00:05:10.799
I see Jamie had something you put in the chat.

00:05:10.799 --> 00:05:13.959
You want to jump in and share that?

00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:14.959
Sure.

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:23.480
So, yesterday, my law firm had speed networking, kind of like speed dating, but not dating,

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:29.839
and I think this just goes to show that in this all-remote universe or remote-by-default

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:33.480
universe, they really have to try hard because they realize people didn't know each other

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:38.640
anymore, but the only people who showed up, with a few exceptions, were people from my

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:49.040
floor who all knew each other, so that was kind of fun, but, you know, people are trying,

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:54.320
but I mean, there's way more happy hours and things like that going on, but not everyone

00:05:54.320 --> 00:06:01.160
goes to those, so there's also happy hours, and, honestly, I feel people get to know each

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:07.239
other more at conferences, like if everybody goes to a conference, you actually get to

00:06:07.239 --> 00:06:12.559
spend more quality time with your peers or people at your company when you're out in

00:06:12.559 --> 00:06:17.559
the wild, so that's kind of another thing I've noticed post-COVID.

00:06:17.559 --> 00:06:21.720
That's such a good point, because I was thinking about that, too, when I used to be in sales

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:27.160
for Posit, I would travel a lot and go to conferences, and you got to go with, like,

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:32.480
one other solutions engineer or sales rep or customer success rep, and you had so many

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:39.160
more experiences with them by getting to travel with them, and I really do miss that part.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.160
Tomas, I see you have your hand raised.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:43.559
Want to jump in?

00:06:43.679 --> 00:06:53.839
Yes, and I'm not sure if there's anyone from FDA on this call right now, but we have this,

00:06:53.839 --> 00:07:01.720
and it's kind of an interesting experience, because we started just as we went remote

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:10.600
because of COVID, we started this sort of an informal Teams channel that was not supposed

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:17.320
to be work, it was kind of just like a hangout, we would, like, just share nonsense and just

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:23.720
talk about anything, and memes and whatever, right?

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:32.000
And it became a really useful venue for this kind of stuff.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:37.640
It's not, I think, it's not, you can't have too many people on it, but you can have, like,

00:07:37.679 --> 00:07:48.239
you know, a good amount of people that are disciplined enough to operate in that kind of space.

00:07:48.239 --> 00:07:55.640
I think it's a little, the problem is that it's a little, there's a generational gap,

00:07:55.640 --> 00:08:02.040
so you don't necessarily, older people are not comfortable with that kind of interaction,

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:07.399
so we're kind of, like, maybe struggling with that a little bit, although we don't, like,

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:12.519
look at it specifically, but it's been really useful to just have something, have this channel

00:08:12.519 --> 00:08:19.119
open all the time, and it's, like, very immediate, and when you're in the middle of something

00:08:19.119 --> 00:08:25.200
and you're chasing a bug and you're frustrated, so you just complain there and you start a

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:29.679
conversation and someone's going to come up with something, but I think the secret is

00:08:29.679 --> 00:08:32.799
that it's totally not structured.

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:42.719
It's really just transient, and there's no record of it, there's no expectation, and

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:51.640
to me, that was really useful, and it really increased my circle of people that I, you

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:56.719
know, can interact with if I need something more specific.

00:08:56.760 --> 00:09:04.080
And I know that, you know, it's sometimes difficult, especially in industrial and government

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:11.640
frameworks to justify this kind of, because people will see it as a waste of time, but

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:16.960
I think that kind of unstructured communication is super important.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:24.960
The moment you put a structure over it, an agenda, and a treasure or whatever, then it

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:31.559
just kills it, but when you have it like this, open, transient, it can be super useful,

00:09:31.559 --> 00:09:38.719
and I think this is what we are doing here, is kind of not that dissimilar, so that's

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:39.719
why.

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:40.719
Yeah, no, that's great.

00:09:40.719 --> 00:09:45.400
The experience, you have to have people that are comfortable with using the Teams channels

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:52.039
and also comfortable with having that kind of conversation and not take over, because

00:09:52.039 --> 00:09:56.280
you will have people that will just take over a channel, and so you have to be disciplined

00:09:56.280 --> 00:09:57.280
in that.

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:01.840
But other than that, I think that's a really good venue for this kind of communication.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:06.280
Definitely, and I was just going to confirm, you said it's a Teams channel?

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:12.200
This is a Teams channel, but it could be, you know, it could be Slack, it could be whatever

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:16.840
you guys, your company or your workplace is using.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:17.840
So we have Teams.

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:18.840
Definitely.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:19.840
Cool.

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:24.239
I see a few other hands raised here if we want to keep going on this topic.

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:25.880
Steve, you want to jump in next?

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:26.880
Yeah, thanks, Rachel.

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:37.440
I was just going to share that our department has a spreadsheet and the statisticians randomize

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:44.840
anybody that wants to be involved, you put your name in, and then within the whole list

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:49.880
within the department, they randomize each other together on a monthly basis.

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:56.119
So every month you get a new person, you can schedule a 15-minute or a 30-minute call and

00:10:56.119 --> 00:10:59.239
just visit with each other and get to know each other.

00:10:59.239 --> 00:11:02.919
So that was one way that our department was doing that.

00:11:02.919 --> 00:11:08.159
We need to do it across departments, I think, too, but within the department, I mean, we've

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:13.840
got a big department, so there's a lot of people that I don't know, and that gives me

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.200
a chance to meet with them.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:17.200
Absolutely.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:22.719
Arati, I see you mentioned you have like a data science Hangout internally.

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:24.520
I'd love to hear about it.

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:31.880
Yeah, we actually have multiple groups in here for each organization in the company.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:36.919
They started something called the Data Science Study Group, and people would just get together

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:42.760
and from various departments, whoever is wanting to transition into analytics or data

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:50.559
science, and they would share goals, and there used to be case studies on how they did data

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:58.679
science in their own teams, and it was a really good forum to exchange knowledge, for sure.

00:11:58.679 --> 00:12:04.679
And I also see that there are some guilds for knowledge exchange going on now.

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:11.200
They meet biweekly, and they usually feature a guest speaker who comes in and talks about

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:16.039
the model that they're developing right now, and they kind of brainstorm about it, and

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:17.039
it's pretty cool.

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:18.039
That's awesome.

00:12:18.039 --> 00:12:19.039
Hey, Rick.

00:12:19.039 --> 00:12:20.039
I see your hand raised.

00:12:20.039 --> 00:12:21.039
Want to jump in?

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:22.039
Good morning, Rachel and colleagues.

00:12:22.039 --> 00:12:23.039
Yes.

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:24.039
I love that you call us all colleagues.

00:12:24.039 --> 00:12:25.039
Well, everybody is.

00:12:25.039 --> 00:12:26.039
Yeah.

00:12:26.039 --> 00:12:27.039
I'm just thrilled to be here.

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:28.039
It's a wonderful thing you and your firm do.

00:12:28.039 --> 00:12:43.960
When I was an industry practitioner for four decades, I found lunch to be the most productive

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:52.119
way to exchange ideas, so for example, I was with a major consulting firm, and those of

00:12:52.119 --> 00:12:56.559
us involved in these kinds of activities would meet for lunch maybe once a week or so, but

00:12:56.559 --> 00:13:02.520
we would discuss models and issues we were having with modeling, and it was like taking

00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:03.520
the right approach.

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:10.440
And I remember one day having a very vigorous discussion about should we have log charts,

00:13:10.440 --> 00:13:17.640
log log charts, or just regular non-log charts as an example, which would be more effective

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:21.440
in communicating the story we were trying to tell.

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:27.440
And we would talk about how to resolve data wrangling issues, because rarely is the data

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:33.000
sets coming out of transactional data stores useful for us in analytical settings and things

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:34.000
like that.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:40.599
Then, when I retired the first time, I joined the faculty of a university, and I became

00:13:40.599 --> 00:13:44.039
a professor for another decade or so.

00:13:44.039 --> 00:13:48.039
And about 10 years ago, we started something we called the Data Science Initiative.

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.039
Now, I think it was Tomas that spoke a few moments ago from the FDA.

00:13:54.039 --> 00:13:59.039
I'm going to respectfully disagree with Tomas.

00:13:59.039 --> 00:14:06.400
For the Data Science Initiative, we wanted to reach out to the campus and our community,

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:13.719
because there were technically oriented organizations in our broader community.

00:14:13.719 --> 00:14:20.520
And what we did for years while I was there, until I retired the second time, we would

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:31.960
host a once-a-month kind of tutorial about some topic about modeling or analysis or interpretation

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:37.719
or we did a lot of, we are our evangelists, I want you to know that.

00:14:37.719 --> 00:14:43.760
In fact, I have a great picture with me with Hadley Wickham, and we're doing the American

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:47.760
Sign Language of R. We were great R advocates.

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:53.320
We were trying to equip others to use these incredible tools.

00:14:53.320 --> 00:15:01.559
But we used the tutorial, about 15 to 20 minutes, as a draw to get people to show up.

00:15:01.559 --> 00:15:07.239
And then we would spend at least an hour, hour and a half, one-on-one, you know, talking

00:15:07.239 --> 00:15:09.919
with people about their specific problems.

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:12.960
Gee, I just can't get this data to line up.

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:14.840
How might you approach this?

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:19.960
You know, this model just goes crazy at this point in time.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:23.400
Things like that, very practically oriented problems.

00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:30.440
So that was our approach, and generally I would agree with Tomas that having a rigorous

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:37.400
scheduled thing might not work, but we used it as a draw to get people there.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:42.280
So they knew they would get some practical little tip like on RStudio or something.

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:44.280
So thank you, Rachel.

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:45.280
Yeah.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:51.640
I think especially for like community groups too, I've seen that having a bunch of different

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:57.239
options works well too, like having the Teams channel, but then having the recurring meeting

00:15:57.239 --> 00:15:58.239
as well.

00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:05.400
Because people want to engage sometimes in different ways, but there's so many great

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:06.880
comments in the chat here.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:12.479
And so I don't know if you want to raise your hand if you have one that you want to share

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:13.479
more broadly.

00:16:13.479 --> 00:16:17.280
But Eric, I see you just raised your hand.

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:18.280
Yeah.

00:16:18.280 --> 00:16:21.280
Just, yeah, just kind of a...

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:22.280
Oops.

00:16:22.280 --> 00:16:23.280
Oh, sorry.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:24.280
Oh, we can hear you.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:25.280
Oh, you can hear me.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:26.280
Okay.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:27.320
Yeah.

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:28.320
Just kind of one...

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:29.320
Sorry.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:30.320
Okay.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:35.640
Just kind of a general comment in terms of like meeting people and stuff and talking

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:38.200
at work is when you work from...

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:44.320
Because in general, like you come to work and like no one can just work nine hours straight

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:45.960
like with zero breaks.

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:50.080
But when you're in an office, the alternative to work is usually like going to grab coffee

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:52.000
or having lunch or something.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.919
But when you work from home, the alternative to work is like maybe you live with someone

00:16:56.919 --> 00:16:59.359
else who works from home or going for a walk.

00:16:59.359 --> 00:17:04.400
You can do that at work too, or just doing stuff around the house.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:11.119
So I've noticed I have to be a little more intentional about communicating with people

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:15.439
and being like, it's okay to go off topic on a Zoom call for 20 minutes because we're

00:17:15.439 --> 00:17:16.439
really just like...

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:21.880
You can think about it like you're at the office versus like...

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:26.040
Because when you're actually at the office, those things just kind of happen organically.

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:30.520
So that's just something I've noticed that you have to be more intentional about making

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:31.520
sure to do it.

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:34.160
Because if not, you could just do work and then not talk to anyone about anything outside

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:37.680
of work because the alternative is like you're already at home, so you can just do other

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:38.680
stuff.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:39.680
Yeah.

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:41.560
That's such a good point too.

00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:45.479
And like reminding yourself that you would have walked around or taken a break at the

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:46.520
office.

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:50.520
You don't have to just be sitting in your home office.

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:51.520
Yeah.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:57.520
I want to encourage people, if there are other topics that you want to cover today or questions

00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:01.439
for you want to ask everybody here to just post them in the chat and Curtis will help

00:18:01.439 --> 00:18:08.439
me grab out the questions too, because I don't want to be the one to kind of determine the

00:18:08.439 --> 00:18:12.719
whole conversation today, but I did want to share something we do at Posit in case it's

00:18:12.719 --> 00:18:16.040
helpful for people here too.

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:23.479
We have these virtual coffees with our president and they started, I don't know, I've been

00:18:23.479 --> 00:18:24.479
here a while.

00:18:24.479 --> 00:18:25.479
I've been here six and a half years now.

00:18:25.479 --> 00:18:31.280
So they started a few years ago, but people can just sign up to join the virtual coffee

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:37.319
and just ask him questions or get to chat with people you might not normally work with.

00:18:37.319 --> 00:18:41.119
