I'm looking for things like that that I can package up and, you know, suggest to students

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:42.320
and other people interested in the topic.

00:51:42.320 --> 00:51:43.679
Yeah, definitely.

00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:49.040
Alan, I see you had a follow-up question here on this topic.

00:51:49.040 --> 00:51:49.679
Want to jump in?

00:51:52.479 --> 00:51:53.120
Yeah, sure.

00:51:53.120 --> 00:51:53.360
Thanks.

00:51:54.639 --> 00:51:59.280
I think my thinking about it was just how to balance that.

00:52:00.719 --> 00:52:01.679
We want to learn.

00:52:01.679 --> 00:52:08.639
It feels really important to be continually learning and being overwhelmed by the number

00:52:08.639 --> 00:52:14.479
of resources that are out there, of communities, of slacks, of discords, of forums and stuff.

00:52:14.479 --> 00:52:21.280
And so, maybe partly just sort of throwing out a line for validation to how hard that

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:21.679
is.

00:52:21.679 --> 00:52:26.159
And maybe to make the comment sort of constructive, I'm finding more and more that I'm leaning

00:52:26.159 --> 00:52:34.879
on my team members to bring stuff to me, and that has its own kind of reward in sort of

00:52:34.879 --> 00:52:40.959
if my role is pivoting a little bit to be more enabling of them, then to the extent

00:52:40.959 --> 00:52:44.399
that they're finding things, they're surfacing, they're bringing them forward, then that's

00:52:44.399 --> 00:52:46.080
also a kind of success.

00:52:46.080 --> 00:52:53.919
And I can be really encouraging and enabling that and realize that when I can't be super

00:52:53.919 --> 00:52:58.320
focused in those kinds of spaces, I can still be helping the folks in my team get rewarded

00:52:58.320 --> 00:53:03.360
by finding new ideas, finding new tools, bringing those into the team, and we can bring those

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:05.439
into our office hours, into our forum, et cetera.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:10.080
And that can be a really nice way to find things at maybe a more manageable scale without

00:53:10.080 --> 00:53:14.080
feeling like I just have to be like drift-netting the internet at all times.

00:53:16.719 --> 00:53:17.280
Definitely.

00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:20.399
Mark, you want to jump in?

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:22.560
Yeah.

00:53:23.199 --> 00:53:33.679
I've actually, I find myself getting into like the, I think it was Patrick Tennant who

00:53:33.679 --> 00:53:39.280
gave like a talk at Posit Conf last year about like the fear of missing out on like awesome

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:40.159
projects or whatnot.

00:53:40.159 --> 00:53:41.840
I find myself falling into that a lot.

00:53:42.159 --> 00:53:51.120
So my solution to Alan's question has basically just been to try to ignore as much as I can

00:53:51.120 --> 00:53:55.919
and just basically focus on whatever it is that we need to do within the org and then

00:53:55.919 --> 00:54:02.399
like, you know, learn what's needed as it comes up, right?

00:54:02.399 --> 00:54:06.320
Because like what you see out, and I'm guilty of this too, of like, when you share something

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:11.600
like, hey, I worked on something really cool, you share that out with other people, right?

00:54:11.600 --> 00:54:14.719
You share that out with the world and it kind of hides like the 99% of the time where

00:54:14.719 --> 00:54:18.639
it's like, okay, I had to like figure out how to clean whatever wonky data set and that

00:54:18.639 --> 00:54:20.800
wasn't fun, but let me show the output, which was really cool.

00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:27.280
So I don't know if that answers Alan's thing, but just another also like public statement

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:32.080
of like, yeah, like it's, there's, that's a very real feeling, the fear of missing out

00:54:32.080 --> 00:54:32.320
there.

00:54:32.320 --> 00:54:43.679
And I, I think it's also to, it's so helpful to try and find ways to connect with people

00:54:43.679 --> 00:54:50.399
who are outside of your typical network as well to like learn new ideas from them.

00:54:50.399 --> 00:54:58.159
We went to this like data content creator meetup in Charleston and I got to hear about

00:54:58.159 --> 00:55:03.919
like all these different tools that I wouldn't be hearing about normally in my everyday work.

00:55:05.679 --> 00:55:11.919
And one of them was, is actually this AI tool for making clips automatically, like short

00:55:11.919 --> 00:55:12.800
little clips.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:17.120
And I was thinking, how can I go and use that for the data science Hangouts?

00:55:17.120 --> 00:55:25.360
And so this week I've just been like experimenting with trying to make a few YouTube shorts from

00:55:25.360 --> 00:55:26.560
the data science Hangouts.

00:55:26.560 --> 00:55:31.280
So there's only three of them right now, but if you want to check it out, I just put

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.840
the YouTube playlist there in the chat.

00:55:37.199 --> 00:55:39.840
And Jamie, I see your hands raised when you jump in.

00:55:40.479 --> 00:55:44.560
Well, I just wanted to mention as much as people are really interested in groups to

00:55:44.560 --> 00:55:49.360
meet up to find out what's new and exciting in data science.

00:55:49.360 --> 00:55:54.639
I think we also have to remember that for a long time, there is this issue with sort

00:55:54.719 --> 00:55:58.080
of like things breaking because of new versions, right?

00:55:58.080 --> 00:56:03.919
And so there was this big movement to come up with like stable package repositories so

00:56:03.919 --> 00:56:10.159
you could learn, so you could always load the same version across everyone who's trying

00:56:10.159 --> 00:56:11.199
to compile your code.

00:56:12.639 --> 00:56:16.560
And rest in peace, Microsoft repository.

00:56:16.879 --> 00:56:24.719
And, you know, Groundhog sort of took the place of the Microsoft repository.

00:56:24.719 --> 00:56:30.080
But I think like there are some things like when RacePredict first came out, I was like,

00:56:30.080 --> 00:56:30.879
oh, that's so cool.

00:56:30.879 --> 00:56:31.919
I want to use that right away.

00:56:31.919 --> 00:56:36.800
But like for the most part, I want other people to use things, find out if it's stable, find

00:56:36.800 --> 00:56:38.159
out if it's buggy, that sort of thing.

00:56:38.159 --> 00:56:42.080
And I don't want to be on the cutting edge unless like maybe there's no other way to

00:56:42.080 --> 00:56:44.080
do it, in which case I'm all in.

00:56:44.080 --> 00:56:49.600
But like I was using like it took me a while to convert from Plyer to dPlyer, right?

00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:52.479
But dPlyer did so much more than Plyer ever did.

00:56:52.479 --> 00:56:53.679
So like that was easy.

00:56:54.959 --> 00:57:00.399
But I think it is sort of like interesting like workarounds, techniques, like the meetups,

00:57:00.399 --> 00:57:05.360
the value I get from the meetups are like how to deal with the reality of computers that

00:57:05.360 --> 00:57:08.159
don't have an infinite amount of memory, that kind of thing.

